{"stages": [
	{"heading":"Stardate 2400.0 (Introduction)",
	"commentary":"<p>Welcome to Doomsday Machine Solitaire. Last time we did this, we opted to see how viable Raiders were against them. Trading out 1 Defense for 1 Attack works pretty good, relative to Cruisers; and they can benefit from 2 of the 4 potential weaknesses without being rendered useless (unlike Fighters and Minelayers) if a non-matching roll is made. This comes at the expense of Cloaking being more expensive to tech up (60 CP total), relative to Ship Size (25 CP total).</p><p>Incidentally, the alternate faction that we will be playing has Cruisers with a similar (but less expensive) style as the original Raiders. Still, we will be stepping it up 1-3 notches (to a map with a hidden Galactic Capitol, and maybe some additional gimmicks). As far as we understand, this map still uses Large's DM strengths, shown in the DM track.</p><p>In addition to playing as one of the alternate factions introduced in All Good Things, having a hidden Galactic Capitol (adjacent to our home systems beyond row J) complicates things a bit. If we uncover it, we can trade with it as if it was a competitive game, but lose the scenario if a Doomsday Machine enters the hex and we do not fend it off.</p>",
